ApplyCurveEffect is used by MultiCurveEffect to apply the curve that is specified by a 2nd input.
It has two inputs and no parameters.
Base3dLutEffect applies a function contained in a 3D look up table. The function samples are interpolated
according to the 3dInterpolationMethod property. The number of samples along the red, green and blue
axes are specified by the RedSampleCount, GreenSampleCount and BlueSampleCount properties. The number
of elements in the 3dLut must be 3 * RedSampleCount * GreenSampleCount * BlueSampleCount.
Warning: Since there are inter-property dependencies among 3dLut, RedSampleCount, GreenSampleCount
and BlueSampleCount, be sure to set these properties all at the same time, coherently. Any render
that occurs in the midst of these may catch the effect in an invalid state, causing a throw to occur.
A 3D table is stored in a 1D array. The array contains output color triplets. In the
input indexing, the first channel (red) changes least rapidly and the last channel
(blue) changes most rapidly. This is the same data organization found in the
multi-dimensional tables of data types 'lut8Type' and 'lut16Type' in ICC color profiles.
The two barycentric methods have identical software implementations, but different
hardware implementations. In hardware, the second version uses fewer texture reads
and has fewer instructions, but uses a larger texture buffer compared to the first.
<property name="RedSampleCount" type ="int" default="33" label="Red samples per axis">
<property name="GreenSampleCount" type ="int" default="33" label="Green samples per axis">
<property name="BlueSampleCount" type ="int" default="33" label="Blue samples per axis">
If the table inputs are linear, enabling perceptual sampling redistributes the
samples is a quasi-perceptual manner (denser sampling near zero and coarser near one).
MakeUniformSample() should be used during the creation of the 3D LUT data table.
BaseCurveEffect applies piecewise linear curve to each channel.
The parameters: Curve0, Curve1, Curve2 and Curve3 are the curves for the corresponding channels.
The possible values for the parameters are:

array of floating point values (can be VT_R4, VT_R8, or VT_VARIANT resolving to VT_R4 or VT_R8), up to the maximal texture size limit (N x 1) of the card (i.e., min(d3dCaps.MaxTextureWidth, d3dCaps.MaxTextureAspectRatio), normally 2048 or 4096)
specifies a curve sampled at equal distance between 0 and 1 (inclusive); as a special case, array of size 1 means a constant curve and an array of size 0 means identity;
the values can be outide of [0, 1] range;
a 2d array of floats [2 x point count], so that each point is represented by a pair (x, y);
the first value of every pair (x) should be in [0, 1] range;
x cannot repeat in any two pairs;
it is recommended to have (x, y) pairs sorted by x.
As usual, a float in an array can be VT_R4, VT_R8, or VT_VARIANT resolving to VT_R4 or VT_R8.

A single-dimensional array is significantly faster as long as array size is the same for all channels (not counting channels with identity curve), because it causes an effect to generate exact small lookup table of the size of an array.

If the input color value is in extended range (i.e., not in [0, 1] range), it is linearly extrapolated using the closest two specified points. If you don't need this support (but your input format can support extended range), for perf optimization, set kszExtendedRangePropertyName ("effect.extendedrange") property on this effect to keStandardRange.
This effect is used by ContrastEffect, ColorExposureEffect, ExposureEffect and ColorTemperatureEffect (via ColorExposureEffect) and possibly many other effects.
BlendEffect blends its Foreground and Background inputs.  The amount of each input in the blended output is
determined by the value of the Opacity property and the optional Mask input.
The blending algorithm is selected with the BlendMode property.
Specifies what percentage of the output image will come from the Background input.
Specifies which blending algorithm to use.
AlphaMode property specifies the formula used to blend alpha channels.
<property name="TreatMaskAlphaZeroAsTransparent" type="bool" default="true" label="Treat mask alpha zero as transparent">
<property name="InputZeroIsForeground" type="bool" default="true" label="Effect input 0 is the foreground layer"/>
Foreground input (index 0) is selected when Opacity == 1.0 unless a mask is specified.
Background input (index 1) is selected when Opacity == 0.0.
Mask input (index 2) determines how much of every Foreground pixel is blended with Background when Opacity > 0.0.
This effect caches requested tiles and is able to stitch cached tiles together
to process subsequent requests without having to request the rest of the
<property name="Test_CacheSizeLimit" type="float" default="1E20" label="Cache size limit (bytes) - Debug only" />
This effect caches requested tiles and is able to stitch them together to process subsequent requests
without having to request the rest of the effect pipeline to re-render everything.
In this version, all cached tiles are actually aligned on a specific, fixed-step grid (e.g. 512x512 grid).
That means that there are no overlapping tiles in cache.
That also guarantees that the effect below will always been called in a consistent manner with the same tile locations and size.
Transforms pixels. The output pixel is the input pixel (vertical vector) multiplied by the matrix specified by the Matrix property, and then added to Translation property.
Used for things like BlackAndWhite and channel swapping where the output pixel is a linear function of the channel values of the input pixel.
<effect label="ColorExposureEffect: adjust black and white points per channel using exposure gain curve">
ColorExposureEffect adjusts black and white points per channel using exposure gain curve.
The parameters: BlackPoint{0..3}.{x|y}, WhitePoint{0..3}.{x|y} are floats or empty.
This effect is used by ExposureEffect and ColorTemperatureEffect.

<effect label="ColorTemperatureEffect: adjust color temperature and tint">
ColorTemperatureEffect adjusts color temperature and green tint of an image.
The limit on temperatures is from 1500 to 15000, but the useful limit is less.
The temperature is in Kelvin degrees. The sun temperature is about 6000 degree K.
There is no limit for green tint adjustment, but the useful limit is from -1 to 1.
If the camera settings and scene parameters are the same, the effect does nothing.
The values to adjust are scene values. The adjustment is the opposite of the image effect;
i.e., adjusting for high scene color temperature will make the image more red, while adjusting for a smaller green tint
Camera setting values are reference values. They specify how you would like the image to look;
i.e., how neutral point should look.
The defaults are 6500 for temperatures and 0.02 for tints. This is slightly warmer than neutral, so that it appears better visually.
AutoFix adjusts SceneTemperature and SceneTint to make neutral point look at CameraSettingsTemperature and CameraSettingsTint.
For asynchronous analysis, use IAutoEffect interface.
<!-- Note: the real possible ranges are higher than that -->
<property name="SceneTemperature" type="float" default="6500" label="Scene color temperature">
<property name="SceneTint" type="float" default="0.02" label="Scene green tint">
<property name="CameraSettingsTemperature" type="float" default="6500" label="Camera settings color temperature">
<property name="CameraSettingsTint" type="float" default="0.02" label="Camera settings green tint">
ContrastEffect adjusts contrast of an image using an S-shaped curve.
The parameter is a floating point scalar that specifies per-channel contrast adjustment.
Zero (default) corresponds to no change. The range is unlimited, but the most useful part is between -1 and 1.

CropEffect will produce image data cropped to the rectangle defined by the Top, Left, Width and Height properties.

Typically the Mode property will be set to None if there is no Crop or if a Crop UI is active. When the user finishes defining a Crop Rectangle with a UI then the Crop Rectangle properties will be set and the Crop Mode will be set to Final.
This Effect adds piecewise cubic spline interpolation capability so users can specify curves with a sparse set of (x, y) control points.
The parameters: CurvePt0, CurvePt1, CurvePt2, CurvePt3 are the control points for the corresponding channels.
The possible values for the parameters are:
A 2D array of floats [2 x point count], so that each point is represented by a pair (x, y).
The floating point values can be VT_R4, VT_R8, or VT_VARIANT resolving to VT_R4 or VT_R8.
The point count must be greater than or equal to two and less than or equal to 18.
The x-coordinates must all differ from each other by at least 0.001.
The control points may be in any order in the array.
A 1D array of floats: x0, y0, x1, y1, etc.
An empty set (VT_EMPTY) will generate a ramp: (0.0, 0.0) to (1.0, 1.0).
<property name="CurvePts0" type="float[]" default="0,0,1,1" label="Control points for Red curve"/>
<property name="CurvePts1" type="float[]" default="0,0,1,1" label="Control points for Green curve"/>
<property name="CurvePts2" type="float[]" default="0,0,1,1" label="Control points for Blue curve"/>
<property name="CurvePts3" type="float[]" default="0,0,1,1" label="Control points for Alpha curve"/>
Curve inversion allows processing of data backwards through the curve set. This is permitted
only for certain types of curves:
a) All curves must be monotonic within the x-interval [0, 1].
b) Within the x-interval [0, 1], the y-value of the curves must be in the range [0, 1].
c) The ClampOutput property must be false.
d) The CurveExtension property must be Extrapolate.
This property applies to all four channels.
Enables or disables clamping of the y-output. If false, no clamping occurs (e.g. CaptureOne
curves behavior). If true, the y-output is clamped to the range [0.0, 1.0] (e.g. PSD curves
behavior). This property applies to all four channels.
Specifies the behavior of the curve to the left of the first control point, and to the right
of the last control point. Extrapolate is used for CaptureOne, and Clamp is used for PSD. This
property applies to all four channels.
This Effect also supports readonly access to the underlying dense curve data
This us useful for supporting the UI display of the dense curve points
For three-point curves, there is a difference between CaptureOne and PSD. The following
property instructs the effect which behavior is wanted. False implies PSD compatibility.
CurveSourceEffect is used by MultiCurveEffect to generate identity curve.
It has no inputs and no parameters.
